{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"92343c01-d45b-4f50-a7fd-b61192494392","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **default test-ID scheme** to fully-qualified names. Azure DevOps matches history by test ID, so every test looks new. To restore continuity, add this to your `.runsettings`:\n\n```xml\n<MSTest>\n  <TestIdGenerationStrategy>Legacy</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n</MSTest>\n```\n\nOr, once you're comfortable losing old history, leave the new IDs in place — they're more robust for disambiguation.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v3 the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` leaked the name of the first test — that was an implementation accident. In v4 no test is in scope yet, so accessing `TestContext.TestName` throws `InvalidOperationException`.\n\nYour fix — remove the dependency on `TestName` in class-level init:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is no longer available here.\n    // Use context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName if you need the class name,\n    // or move per-test logic to [TestInitialize].\n}\n```\n\nIf you need per-test setup, use `[TestInitialize]` instead:\n\n```csharp\n[TestInitialize]\npublic void TestInit()\n{\n    var testName = TestContext.TestName; // works fine here\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. Other v4 changes to watch for\n\n| Area | What changed |\n|---|---|\n| **Parallelization** | Class-level parallelism is now **on by default**. Add `[assembly: Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.MethodLevel)]` or `Disable` if tests have shared state. |\n| **Assert.Inconclusive** | Now throws `AssertInconclusiveException` instead of being silently treated as a pass in some runners. |\n| **Timeout** | `[Timeout]` applies to the test body only; setup/cleanup have separate timeout controls. |\n| **DataRow / DynamicData** | Display-name generation changed, which can also affect ADO test-history matching. |\n| **Removed APIs** | Several long-deprecated members on `TestContext` (e.g., `DataConnection`, `DataRow`) are removed entirely. |\n\nWould you like me to update your `SetupTests.cs` to be v4-compatible?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b838cfdc-04d9-48fe-b596-9c0733b0d5d6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me provide what I know about MSTest v4 changes, specifically addressing their two issues and general migration concerns.\n\nKey MSTest v4 breaking changes I know about:\n\n1. **Fully qualified test IDs** — MSTest v4 changed the default test ID format to use fully qualified names. This causes Azure DevOps (and other test management tools) to see every test as \"new\" because the IDs changed. This explains the lost test history.\n\n2. **TestContext in ClassInitialize** — In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` methods is no longer associated with a specific test. Accessing `TestContext.TestName` (and other test-specific properties) throws an `InvalidOperationException` because at class-initialization time there is no test running yet. In v3 this happened to return the name of the first test method, which was arguably a bug/leak of implementation detail.\n   \n3. Beyond these two, there are several other breaking changes worth noting: `DeploymentItem` attributes behave differently, `DataRow` attributes have changed, some deprecated APIs were removed entirely, test parallelization defaults shifted, and `TestContext` properties now have stricter scoping rules depending on whether they're test-specific or class-level.","outputTokens":930,"requestId":"7C1C:14C11A:1A1082D:1D92622:69F95F5B"},"id":"3dbf768a-5306-41a1-b388-eca246eb490b","timestamp":"2026-05-05T03:09:37.956Z","parentId":"c9aa5d12-1113-41f6-b2b7-56e75a498cf6"}
